      <h2 id="about-tool-heading" class="font-display font-semibold text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-primary tracking-tight">
        The Science & Practice of White Noise for Sleep & Focus
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Struggling to stay focused during work, or tossing and turning trying to fall asleep? Our free, local <strong>white noise</strong> machine offers a powerful, science-backed auditory environment designed to help you concentrate, sleep deeply, and calm a crying baby. Unlike basic audio loops that can interrupt your circadian rhythm with sudden seam changes, our browser-based tool synthesizes pure, loop-free white noise in real-time, right inside your browser.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-primary mt-2">
        What is White Noise and How Does it Work?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        To understand <strong>what is white noise</strong>, think of it as the auditory equivalent of white light. Just as white light contains every wavelength of the visible spectrum combined, white noise is a steady sound that contains all frequencies across the range of human hearing (20 to 20,000 Hz) in equal measure. This creates a uniform hum—often described as static hiss, light rain, or rushing wind.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        The secret behind why it works so well lies in a phenomenon called <strong>auditory masking</strong>. When your room is completely quiet, your brain becomes highly sensitive to sudden auditory spikes, like a passing car, a barking dog, or a floorboard creak. These sudden shifts in volume trigger the brain's alert system, waking you from sleep or disrupting your deep focus. By creating a continuous blanket of background sound, white noise raises the ambient audio baseline, meaning those sudden noise spikes no longer stand out. The auditory cortex simply filters them out.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-primary mt-2">
        Brown Noise vs. White Noise: Which is Better?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        If you have researched sound therapy, you have likely come across the debate of <strong>brown noise vs white noise</strong>. While white noise distributes equal energy across all frequencies, its high-frequency tones can sound somewhat bright or sharp to some ears.
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm sm:text-base text-slate flex flex-col gap-2">
        <li><strong>White Noise:</strong> Bright and airy, similar to radio static or a rushing waterfall. It is highly effective for blocking high-pitched sounds and relieving tinnitus.</li>
        <li><strong>Brown Noise:</strong> Deeper and richer, lowering the volume of higher frequencies and emphasizing deep bass. It sounds like a heavy ocean surf, a distant thunder rumble, or a low jet engine hum.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Choosing the <strong>best online white noise</strong> setup depends entirely on your environment and preference. Using our generator's low-pass filter, you can easily shift between white and brown noise profiles to find the exact tone that works for your ears.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-primary mt-2">
        Is it Safe to Use a White Noise Machine for Babies?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Many new parents rely on a <strong>white noise machine</strong> or a <strong>white noise app</strong> to help soothe a crying infant. The sound mimics the loud, rushing environment of the womb, triggering the baby's natural calming reflex. However, it is essential to follow safe listening guidelines to protect your baby's sensitive hearing.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        The <strong>best white noise for baby</strong> is kept at a moderate, safe volume of around 50 decibels—equivalent to a quiet conversation or a gentle shower. Never place the sound source directly inside the crib or right next to the infant's head. Instead, place it at least 6 to 7 feet (2 meters) away from the sleep area and set a gentle sleep timer so it fades out automatically once they are fast asleep.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-primary mt-2">
        Why Choose Web-Based Audio Over Native Apps?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm sm:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Our local audio generator is a highly efficient alternative to native applications. Instead of downloading massive MP3 files or streaming endless audio clips that drain your battery and consume mobile data, this tool uses the Web Audio API to synthesize sound waves directly on your computer or phone. This means the audio is 100% private, runs entirely offline, and delivers a clean, seamless soundscape indefinitely. Whether you are using it as a study aid, a sound shield for office distractions, or a <strong>free white noise for sleep</strong> companion, you can enjoy customized tranquility without advertisements or tracking.
      </p>
